        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName>Down Bromley | Kent</placeName>
                    <date>Wednesday</date>
                    <salute>Dear Sir</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
    
<p>The Geological map of S. America was not sent me with D’Orbigny’s work—<ref target="#foot.f2"/> would you please send it me <hi rend="underline">and a</hi> <hi rend="underline">card of the Evening meetings</hi> <ref target="#foot.f3"/> —either by Post, or if <hi rend="underline">there are any parcels waiting for me</hi>, by “<hi rend="underline">Down</hi> <hi rend="underline">Coach</hi>”, from Bolt-in-Tun Fleet St.—<ref target="#foot.f4"/></p>
<p>Yours faithfully | C. Darwin</p>
<p>Coach starts daily at 3 olock.</p> 
                </div>
            </div>
                <div type="tnotes">
                    <note xml:id="tnote.n1">1.2 Evening] ‘E’ <hi rend="italic">over</hi> ‘e’</note>
                    <note xml:id="tnote.n2">1.3 "<hi rend="italic">Down</hi>] <hi rend="italic">interl</hi></note>
                </div>

        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">Dated from surrounding letters in the Geological Society Letter Book, all of which are dated in the first week of January 1844.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2"><ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_6005.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Orbigny 1835–47</ref>, vol. 3, pt 3: <hi rend="italic">Géologie</hi>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3">CD was vice-president of the Society in 1844.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f4">A tavern from which coaches started for the south of England.</note>
        </div>        
            
